 Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabell Trewithian was born in 1365, in England, United Kingdom, her father, William Trewithian, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. William Trewithian, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Reginald Wolvedon. She died in 1435, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1365–1435":"1365–1435","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1338":"1338","1435":"1435","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","Wolvedon, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1365–1435":"1365–1435","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut"